pace: 0pt;">
<table class=3D"body-component" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"=
0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff was supposed to be off today, but: bank run!</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SVB</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lesson might be that there are some indust=
ries that are bad to bank. Imagine that it was 2021, and someone was like =
=E2=80=9Cdo you want to start the Bank of Crypto? What about the Bank of Ve=
nture-Backed Tech Startups?=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99d be=C2=A0tempted, right? =
Those industries had so much money! They seemed cool. If you were their ban=
k =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you were the specialized bank that exclusively focused =
on those industries =E2=80=94=C2=A0influencers on Twitter would tweet nice =
things about you, and you=E2=80=99d get invited to fancy parties. Also, as =
their bank, you=E2=80=99d probably=C2=A0find a way to get a cut of growing =
industries with lots of potential. Provide banking services to tech startup=
s, get warrants in those startups, get rich when they go public. Provide ba=
nking services to crypto exchanges, start some sort of blockchain-based pay=
ment network, get rich through the magic of saying =E2=80=9Cblockchain=E2=
=80=9D a lot.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the structure of being the Bank of Crypto =
or Startups was a bit rickety. Traditionally, the way a bank works is that =
it takes deposits from people who have money, and makes loans to people who=
 need money. The weird problem with focusing exclusively on=C2=A0crypto or =
startups in 2021 is that they had too much money. If you were the Bank of S=
tartups, the main service that you provided to startups is that equity inve=
stors=C2=A0=C2=A0would give them a truck full of cash and they=E2=80=99d de=
posit it at your bank. Here is how SVB Financial Group, the holding company=
 of Silicon Valley Bank, describes the vibe of 2021 and 2022 in its <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30799833.257405/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jZ2ktYmluL2Jyb3dzZS1lZGdhcj9jb21wYW55PSZDSUs9c2l2YiZmaWxl=
bnVtPSZTdGF0ZT0mU0lDPSZvd25lcj1leGNsdWRlJmFjdGlvbj1nZXRjb21wYW55/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBe4b33a8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Form 10-K two weeks ago</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much of the recent deposit growth =
was driven by our clients across all segments obtaining liquidity through l=
iquidity events, such as IPOs, secondary offerings, SPAC fundraising, ventu=
re capital investments, acquisitions and other fundraising activities=E2=80=
=94which during 2021 and early 2022 were at notably high levels.</p></block=
quote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People kept flinging money at SVB=E2=80=99s cu=
stomers, and they kept depositing it at SVB.=C2=A0Perfectly reasonable bank=
ing service.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the customers=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t need loa=
ns, in part because equity investors kept giving them trucks full of cash a=
nd in part because young tech startups tend not to have the fixed assets or=
 recurring cash flows that make for good corporate borrowers.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Oh, there is <em>some=C2=A0</em>tech-industry-adjacent lending yo=
u can do.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Tech founders want to buy houses, and you can give them mortgages. Ven=
ture capital and private equity funds want to manage liquidity and/or juice=
 their reported return rates by paying for investments with borrowed money =
rather than=C2=A0drawing from their limited partners, so you can get into t=
he capital-call-line-of-credit business. There are vineyards near Silicon V=
alley=C2=A0and you can develop an expertise in vineyard financing. And, sur=
e, some of your tech-company customers=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>need to borrow=
 money, and=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>creditworthy, and you lend them money an=
d that works out. But there is a basic imbalance. Customer money keeps comi=
ng in, as deposits, but it doesn=E2=80=99t go out, as loans.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you have all this customer cash, and you ne=
ed to do something with it. Keeping it in, like, Fed reserves, or Treasury =
bills, in 2021, was not a great choice; that stuff paid basically no intere=
st, and you want to make money. So you=E2=80=99d buy longer-dated, but also=
 very safe, securities, things like Treasury bonds and agency mortgage-back=
ed securities. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
30799833.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjMtMDMtMDkvY3J5cHRvLWJhbmstaGFkLWEtYm9yaW5nLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMT=
AyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0b=
V90ZXJtPTIzMDMxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
a3c89450" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about how this worked out at Silve=
rgate Capital Corp., the actual Bank of Crypto. And as of <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30799833.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2V=
jLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvNzE5NzM5LzAwMDA3MTk3MzkyMzAwMD=
AyMS9zaXZiLTIwMjIxMjMxLmh0bSNpYmI0ZGQ3M2ExZDNmNGJmZjk0NGI1ZDM1ZmQyYzVlMmFfM=
Tg0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1461cc07" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the end of 2022</a>, Silico=
n Valley Bank, the actual Bank of Startups, had about $74 billion of loans =
and about $120 billion of investment securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crudely stereotyping, in traditional banking, =
you take deposits and make loans. In the Bank of Startups, in 2021, you tak=
e deposits and mostly buy bonds. Again crudely stereotyping,=C2=A0corporate=
 loans often have floating interest rates and shorter terms, while bonds ha=
ve=C2=A0fixed<em>=C2=A0</em>interest rates and longer terms. None of this i=
s completely true =E2=80=94=C2=A0there are fixed-rate corporate loans and f=
loating-rate bonds, traditional banking tends to involve making lots of loa=
ns (like mortgages) with long-term=C2=A0fixed rates,=C2=A0you can do swaps,=
 etc.=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is a useful crude stereotype.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or, to put it in different crude terms, in tra=
ditional banking, you make your money in part by taking credit risk: You ge=
t to know your customers, you try to get good at knowing which of them will=
 be able to pay back loans, and then you make loans to those good customers=
. In the Bank of Startups, in 2021, you couldn=E2=80=99t really make money =
by taking credit risk: Your customers just didn=E2=80=99t need enough credi=
t to give you the credit risk that you needed to make money on all those de=
posits. So you had to make your money by taking interest-rate risk: Instead=
 of making loans to risky corporate borrowers, you bought long-term bonds b=
acked by the US government.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result of this is that, as the Bank of Sta=
rtups, you were unusually exposed to interest-rate risk. Most banks, when i=
nterest rates go up, have to pay=C2=A0more interest on deposits, but get pa=
id=C2=A0more interest on their loans, and end up profiting from rising inte=
rest rates. But you, as the Bank of Startups, own a lot of long-duration bo=
nds, and their market value goes down as rates go up. Every bank has some m=
ix of this =E2=80=94=C2=A0every bank borrows short to lend=C2=A0long; that=
=E2=80=99s what banking is=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but many banks end up a bit =
more balanced than the Bank of Startups. At the Financial Times,=C2=A0<a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30799833.257405/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvN2NmNGViNDUtNzhiNy00ZTZlLWIxMzQtMWYwYjA4MmJhMj=
Az/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb71a92f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Robert Armstrong writes</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Few other banks have as much of their assets l=
ocked up in fixed-rate securities as SVB, rather than in floating-rate loan=
s. Securities are 56 per cent of SVB=E2=80=99s assets. At Fifth Third, the =
figure is 25 per cent; at Bank of America, it is 28 per cent.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For most banks higher rates, in and of themsel=
ves, are good news. They help the asset side of the balance sheet more than=
 they hurt the liability side. =E2=80=A6 SVB is the opposite: higher rates =
hurt it on the liability side more than they help it on the asset side. As =
Oppenheimer bank analyst Chris Kotowski sums up, SVB is =E2=80=9Ca liabilit=
y-sensitive outlier in a generally asset-sensitive world=E2=80=9D.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is another, subtler, more dangerous =
exposure to interest rates: You are the Bank of Startups, and <em>startups =
are a low-interest-rate phenomenon</em>. When interest rates are low everyw=
here, a dollar in 20 years is about as good as a dollar today, so a startup=
 whose business model is =E2=80=9Cwe will lose money for a decade building =
artificial intelligence, and then rake in lots of money in the far future=
=E2=80=9D sounds pretty good. When interest rates are higher, a dollar toda=
y is better than a dollar tomorrow, so investors want cash flows. When inte=
rest rates were low for a long time, and suddenly become high, all the mone=
y that was rushing to your customers is suddenly cut off. Your clients who =
were =E2=80=9Cobtaining liquidity through liquidity events, such as IPOs, s=
econdary offerings, SPAC fundraising, venture capital investments, acquisit=
ions and other fundraising activities=E2=80=9D stop doing that. Your custom=
ers keep taking money out of the bank to pay rent and salaries, but they st=
op depositing new money.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all even more true of crypto =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0I mean,=C2=A0the Fed raised rates once and the entire crypto industry=
 vanished?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94 but it is not <em>not</em> true of startups. But if som=
e charismatic tech founder=C2=A0had come to you in 2021 and said =E2=80=9CI=
 am going to revolutionize the world via [artificial intelligence][robot ta=
xis][flying taxis][space taxis][blockchain],=E2=80=9D it might have felt un=
natural to reply =E2=80=9Cnah but what if the Fed raises rates by 0.25%?=E2=
=80=9D This was an industry with a radical vision for the future of humanit=
y, not a bet on interest rates. Turns out it was a bet on interest rates th=
ough.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30799833.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvdGhlLXdlZWtseS1maXgtam9icy1kYXktY291=
bGQtbWFrZS1vci1icmVhay1iZXRzLW9uLTUwLWJhc2lzLXBvaW50cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzEwMjN=
fTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdG=
VybT0yMzAzMTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfd75=
e90a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Katie Greifeld</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silvergate and SVB =E2=80=9Cin fac=
t are victims of the same phenomenon as Fed tightening extinguishes froth f=
rom those parts of the economy with the most excess =E2=80=94 and it=E2=80=
=99s hard to find more excess than in crypto and tech startups,=E2=80=9D sa=
id Adam Crisafulli of Vital Knowledge.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And my Bloomberg Opinion colleague <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30799833.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3ZiLWFuZC1zaWx2=
ZXJnYXRlLWJhbmstdHVtdWx0LWluLWNhbGlmb3JuaWEtaGFzLWVjaG9lcy1pbi10ZXhhcy1jcml=
zaXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMxMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cm=
NlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBffb7df91" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Paul Davies</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both crypto and venture capital bo=
oms were children of the ultra-low rates of the past decade and a half. Now=
, rising rates and the shrinking of the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s balance s=
heet have burst those industry bubbles and increased the competition among =
banks for funding.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you were the Bank of Startups, just =
like if you were the Bank of Crypto, it turned out that you had made a huge=
 concentrated bet on interest rates. Your customers were flush with cash, s=
o they gave you all that cash, but they didn=E2=80=99t need loans so you in=
vested all that cash in longer-dated fixed-income securities, which lost va=
lue when rates went up. But also, when rates went up, your customers all go=
t smoked, because it turned out that=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>were creatures=
 of low interest rates, and in a higher-interest-rate environment they didn=
=E2=80=99t have money anymore. So they withdrew their deposits, so you had =
to sell those securities at a loss to pay them back. Now you have lost mone=
y and look financially shaky,=C2=A0so customers get spooked and withdraw mo=
re money, so you sell more securities, so you book more losses,=C2=A0oops o=
ops oops.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Armstrong puts it, SVB had =E2=80=9Ca doubl=
e sensitivity to higher interest rates. On the asset side of the balance sh=
eet, higher rates decrease the value of those long-term debt securities. On=
 the liability side, higher rates mean less money shoved at tech, and as su=
ch, a lower supply of cheap deposit funding.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, I am sorry to be rude, but there is anot=
her reason that it is maybe not great to be the Bank of Startups, which is =
that nobody on Earth is more of a herd animal=C2=A0than Silicon Valley vent=
ure capitalists. What you want, as a bank, is a certain amount of diversity=
 among your depositors. If some depositors get spooked and take their money=
 out, and other depositors evaluate your balance sheet and decide things ar=
e fine and keep their money in, and lots more depositors keep their money i=
n because they simply don=E2=80=99t pay attention to banking news, then you=
 have a shot at muddling through your problems.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if all of your depositors are startups wit=
h=C2=A0the same handful of venture capitalists on their boards, and all tho=
se venture capitalists are competing with each other to Add Value and Be In=
fluencers and Do The Current Thing by calling all their portfolio companies=
 to say =E2=80=9Chey, did you hear, everyone=E2=80=99s taking money out of =
Silicon Valley Bank, you should too,=E2=80=9D then all of your depositors w=
ill take their money out at the same time. In fact, <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30799833.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMDkvc3ZiLWNlby1iZWNrZXItYXNrcy1zaWxp=
Y29uLXZhbGxleS1iYW5rLWNsaWVudHMtdG8tc3RheS1jYWxtP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMTAyM19NT05=
FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPT=
IzMDMxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB10862c2f"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">  Bloomberg reported yesterday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unease is spreading across the financial world=
 as concerns about the stability of Silicon Valley Bank prompt prominent ve=
nture capitalists including Peter Thiel=E2=80=99s Founders Fund to advise s=
tartups to withdraw their money. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Founders Fund asked its portfolio companies to=
